{
  "doc_id": "30177",
  "text": "Isoforms of the cytochrome P450 (CYP) 3A subfamily are the most abundantly expressed CYP enzymes in the human liver [CITATION_1] . In adults, CYP3A4 and CYP3A5 are predominant among the four known isoforms (CYP3A4, CYP3A5, CYP3A7, and CYP3A43) in the liver and intestines [CITATION_2] . However, metabolically active CYP3A5 is expressed only by an estimated 10% to 30% of Caucasians and 50% to 60% of African Americans [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The genetic basis for polymorphically expressed CYP3A5 was recently reported to be associated with a single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) in intron 3 of the CYP3A5 gene (CYP3A5*3C; refs. [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . This SNP causes alternative splicing and truncation of CYP3A5 protein and provides the basis for the absence of CYP3A5 protein in most individuals of Caucasian descent. In people with at least one CYP3A5*1A wild-type allele, CYP3A5 accounts for at least 50% of the total CYP3A content, and results in f2-to 3-fold higher total CYP3A activity in vitro [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . The most prevalent polymorphism in CYP3A4 (CYP3A4*1B) occurs in the 5V flanking region of the gene. The frequency of this allele ranges from 2% to 9.6% in Caucasians to 35% to 67% in African Americans [CITATION_9] .",
